Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist0:Thought: The core challenge in pseudo-label-based self-training lies in the tension between confidence and generalization. When models assign pseudo-labels to unlabeled data, overly confident but incorrect labels can propagate noise and degrade performance—a phenomenon exacerbated when temperature scaling is fixed and static. Inspired by Paper 1’s use of adaptive temperature for calibration, Paper 3’s differentiable teacher-student dynamics, and the broader need for dynamic control in learning systems, I propose a novel framework that learns an adaptive temperature policy conditioned on uncertainty, consistency, and feature-space density. Unlike ATS, which applies post-hoc calibration using token-level features, our method integrates adaptive temperature directly into contrastive self-training as a learnable, input-dependent policy that modulates both classification and representation learning. This goes beyond mere calibration: it actively shapes the student’s learning trajectory by balancing exploitation (high-confidence pseudo-labels) and exploration (uncertain regions where temperature is increased to soften predictions). Furthermore, unlike DRIFT’s game-theoretic formulation that focuses on weight differentiation, we introduce a meta-learned temperature controller that dynamically adjusts based on three principled signals: prediction entropy (uncertainty), agreement across augmentations (consistency), and local feature density (to detect out-of-distribution or sparse regions). By making temperature a function of these context-aware metrics rather than a global hyperparameter, the model becomes more robust to label noise and better at generalizing across diverse data distributions. The integration with contrastive learning adds another layer of benefit—while pseudo-labels guide categorical alignment, contrastive loss ensures semantic smoothness in the embedding space. Our approach thus unifies representation learning and label refinement under a single adaptive mechanism, enabling safer and more effective use of unlabeled data.

