  "Idea": "We propose MetaTemp-CT (Meta-Learned Temperature Control for Contrastive Self-Training), a novel framework that leverages a pre-trained meta-calibration network to dynamically adjust the softmax temperature during pseudo-label generation in semi-supervised learning. Unlike existing approaches that either use fixed temperatures or learn them through complex online bilevel optimization (e.g., LATE-CT), MetaTemp-CT employs a lightweight, generalizable meta-network trained offline on a broad corpus of training trajectories across multiple datasets (CIFAR-10/100, STL-10, TinyImageNet), label ratios (1%–50%), and corruption levels. This meta-network takes as input three real-time signals extracted from the student model: (1) predictive uncertainty (entropy over class probabilities), (2) inter-augmentation consistency (symmetric KL divergence between two augmented views), and (3) class-conditional feature-space density (computed via kNN distances within predicted class clusters in the encoder space). To address class imbalance and avoid overconfident labeling in underrepresented regions, we introduce a normalized density score that adjusts for relative class frequency in the neighborhood. The output of the meta-network is a scalar temperature value applied to the softmax operator used in pseudo-label generation and also modulates the sampling distribution in the contrastive loss (e.g., reweighting positive pairs based on alignment confidence). The meta-network itself is trained using a meta-objective that minimizes the discrepancy between predicted temperatures and oracle temperatures derived from ablation studies—specifically, those temperatures that maximize validation accuracy while minimizing expected calibration error (ECE) over rolling windows in training. Once trained, the meta-network acts as a plug-in module that requires no fine-tuning and can be deployed across new tasks with minimal adaptation. This design enables fast, stable, and interpretable temperature control without the computational overhead of implicit differentiation or second-order gradients. We further enhance robustness by incorporating a gating mechanism that disables temperature updates when prediction entropy exceeds a threshold, preventing harmful propagation of noisy labels. MetaTemp-CT bridges the gap between post-hoc calibration (like ATS) and online self-training dynamics, offering a best-of-both-worlds solution: adaptivity without instability. We evaluate MetaTemp-CT on standard benchmarks under extreme label scarcity (e.g., 1k labels on CIFAR-100) and domain-shift conditions (e.g., CIFAR-C). We expect significant improvements in top-1 accuracy (>4% over FixMatch), reduced ECE (by ~60%), and better label efficiency, particularly in imbalanced settings. Ablation studies will assess the contribution of each input signal and the impact of class-aware density normalization.",
