Both Idea 0 (LATE-CT) and Idea 1 (MetaTemp-CT) propose highly novel approaches to adaptive temperature control in contrastive self-training, leveraging uncertainty, consistency, and feature-space density to modulate pseudo-labeling confidence. However, when evaluating against the provided related work, novelty must be assessed not only in isolation but also in terms of differentiation from existing mechanisms such as ATS (Paper 3), curriculum temperature (Paper 4), meta-learning for instance weighting (Paper 5), and meta-learning via in-context tuning (Paper 2).

Idea 0 proposes an end-to-end bilevel optimization framework where a *learned* temperature policy network is trained jointly with the model using implicit differentiation. This approach tightly integrates temperature adaptation into the training dynamics and extends it to both classification and contrastive losses. While powerful, this bears conceptual similarity to meta-learning with implicit gradients as seen in classical MAML variants or DaMSTF (Paper 5), which also uses meta-learning within self-training and constructs validation signals for learning instance importance. Although LATE-CT applies this to temperature control, the core mechanism—bilevel optimization with online meta-updates—is well-established in meta-learning literature, reducing its *relative* novelty despite technical sophistication.

In contrast, Idea 1 (MetaTemp-CT) introduces a **pre-trained, generalizable meta-network** that is trained offline on a broad corpus of training trajectories across datasets and conditions to predict "oracle" temperatures. This plug-and-play design avoids costly online second-order updates and instead leverages cross-task regularities—a true meta-learning paradigm akin to learning heuristics from experience. Crucially, none of the provided papers describe a system where a meta-model is trained *across diverse semi-supervised training dynamics* to generalize temperature control. Paper 3 (ATS) is post-hoc and static; Paper 4 (CTKD) uses a heuristic schedule; Paper 5 (DaMSTF) focuses on sample weighting in domain adaptation, not temperature modulation across tasks. MetaTemp-CT’s use of class-aware density normalization and gating further enhances robustness in low-data regimes, while its deployment simplicity without fine-tuning offers practical advantages.

Moreover, the idea of distilling cross-dataset insights into a reusable calibration controller represents a shift from per-experiment tuning to systematic, transferable calibration intelligence—an underexplored direction in self-training. This broader generalization capability makes MetaTemp-CT more *distinctively novel* than LATE-CT, which remains confined to online adaptation within a single run.

Thus, while both ideas are strong, **Idea 1** achieves greater novelty by decoupling meta-learning from online bilevel optimization and instead proposing a reusable, off-the-shelf adaptive module trained over diverse task distributions—an approach not reflected in any of the provided papers.

